# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cattle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The **10th edition of *Systema Naturae*** (Latin; the English title is *A General System of Nature*) is a book written by Swedish naturalist Carl Linnaeus and published in two volumes in 1758 and 1759, which marks the starting point of zoological nomenclature.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In it, Linnaeus introduced binomial nomenclature for animals, something he had already done for plants in his 1753 publication of *Species Plantarum*.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Before 1758, most biological catalogues had used polynomial names for the taxa included, including earlier editions of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The first work to consistently apply binomial nomenclature across the animal kingdom was the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature therefore chose 1 January 1758 as the "starting point" for zoological nomenclature and asserted that the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae* was to be treated as if published on that date.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Names published before that date are unavailable, even if they would otherwise satisfy the rules.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The only work which takes priority over the 10th edition is Carl Alexander Clerck's **Svenska Spindlar** or **Aranei Suecici**, which was published in 1757, but is also to be treated as if published on January 1, 1758.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] During Linnaeus' lifetime, *Systema Naturae* was under continuous revision.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Progress was incorporated into new and ever-expanding editions; for example, in his 1st edition (1735), whales and manatees were originally classified as species of fish (as was thought to be the case then).
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In the 10th edition, they were both moved into the mammal class.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The animal kingdom, as described by Linnaeus: "Animals enjoy sensation by means of a living organization, animated by a medullary substance; perception by nerves; and motion by the exertion of the will.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They have members for the different purposes of life; organs for their different senses; and faculties (or powers) for the application of their different perceptions.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The list has been broken down into the original six classes Linnaeus described for animals: **Mammalia**, **Aves**, **Amphibia**, **Pisces**, **Insecta**, and **Vermes**.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] By current standards Pisces and Vermes are informal groupings, Insecta also contained arachnids and crustaceans, and one order of Amphibia comprised sharks, lampreys, and sturgeons.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described mammals as: "Animals that suckle their young by means of lactiferous teats.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In external and internal structure they resemble man: most of them are quadrupeds; and with man, their natural enemy, inhabit the surface of the Earth.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described birds as: "A beautiful and cheerful portion of created nature consisting of animals having a body covered with feathers and down; protracted and naked jaws (the beak), two wings formed for flight, and two feet.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described fish as: "Always inhabiting the waters; are swift in their motion and voracious in their appetites.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They breathe by means of gills, which are generally united by a bony arch; swim by means of radiate fins, and are mostly covered over with cartilaginous scales.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described his "Vermes" as: "Animals of slow motion, soft substance, able to increase their bulk and restore parts which have been destroyed, extremely tenacious of life, and the inhabitants of moist places.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Many of them are without a distinct head, and most of them without feet.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They are principally distinguished by their tentacles (or feelers).
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The second volume, published in 1759, detailed the kingdom Plantae, in which Linnaeus included true plants, as well as fungi, algae and lichens.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In addition to repeating the species he had previously listed in his *Species Plantarum* (1753), and those published in the intervening period, Linnaeus described several hundred new plant species.
[src:cattle/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The species from *Species Plantarum* were numbered sequentially, while the new species were labelled with letters.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] Abbott's duikers stand around 65 cm (26 in) tall at the shoulder and weigh about 55 kg (121 lb).
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] This duiker has a glossy, dark brown coat which is lighter on the underside.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] The face is paler and grey in colour, with a large red tuft on the forehead; the horns are thin and short (8 to 12 cm (3.1 to 4.7 in)).
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] The secretive behaviour of Abbott's duiker, along with its largely nocturnal habits and preference for dense vegetation, means little is known about the ecology and behaviour of this species.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] It has been observed feeding on leaves in the forest understory, and on vegetation in forest clearings, and may feed on fruits, flowers and moss.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] An Abbott's duiker has also been seen with a frog in its mouth; duikers are known to capture and feed on live prey occasionally.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] The cryptic habits and alertness of Abbott's duiker unfortunately does not protect it entirely from predation.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] Young Abbott's duikers are probably preyed on by African crowned eagles (*Stephanoetus coronatus*) and pythons (*Python*species; *Python natalensis* and *Python sebae*), while duikers of all ages may fall victim to leopards (*Panthera pardus*).
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] Abbott's duiker is endemic to Tanzania, in the Eastern Arc Mountains, Mount Kilimanjaro, and Southern Highlands in scattered populations.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] They live mainly in wet forests and swamps between 1,700 and 2,700 m above sea level, but can sometimes wander to much higher elevations at 4,000 m.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] They eat mainly fruit and possibly other plant matter.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] Abbott's duikers are nocturnal, spending the days at rest in thickets.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] They form regular pathways through the undergrowth, making them relatively easy to find.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] If threatened, they generally try to run, though they have been known to kill pursuing dogs when left with no escape route.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] Less than 1,500 Abbott's duiker are estimated to be left in the world, with no captive population.
[src:cattle/abbott-s-duiker] They are threatened by habitat destruction and poaching.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The **Aberdeen Angus**, sometimes simply **Angus**, is a Scottish breed of small beef cattle.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] It derives from cattle native to the counties of Aberdeen, Banff, Kincardine and Angus in north-eastern Scotland.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] In 2018, it accounted for over 17% of the beef production in the United Kingdom.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The Angus is naturally polled and solid black or red; the udder may be white.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The cattle have been exported to many countries of the world; there are large populations in Australia, Canada, New Zealand, South America and the United States, where it has developed into two separate and distinct breeds, the American Angus and the Red Angus.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] In some countries it has been bred to be taller than the native Scottish stock.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Its conservation status worldwide is "not at risk"; in the United Kingdom the original Native Aberdeen Angus – cattle not influenced by cross-breeding with imported stock – is listed by the Rare Breeds Survival Trust as "at risk".
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] For some time before the 1800s, the hornless cattle in Angus were called "Angus Doddies", while those in the historic province of Buchan (later part of Aberdeenshire) were known as "Buchan Humlies", both "doddie" and "humlie" meaning “polled”.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] In 1824, William McCombie of Tillyfour, later the Member of Parliament for West Aberdeenshire, began to improve the stock and is regarded today as the father of the breed.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The breed was officially recognised in 1835, and was initially registered together with the Galloway in the Polled Herd Book.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The cattle became commonplace throughout the British Isles in the mid-twentieth century.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] As stated in the fourth volume of the Herd Book of the UK's Angus, this breed was introduced to Argentina in 1879 when "*Don* Carlos Guerrero" imported one bull and two cows for his *Estancia* "Charles" located in Juancho, Partido de General Madariaga, Provincia de Buenos Aires.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The bull was born on 19 April 1878; named "Virtuoso 1626" and raised by Colonel Ferguson.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The cows were named "Aunt Lee 4697" raised by J.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Walker and were both born in 1878, on 31 January and 23 April respectively.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Angus cattle were first introduced to Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) in the 1820s, and to the southern mainland in 1840.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The breed is now found in all Australian states and territories with 62000 calves registered with Angus Australia in 2010.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] In 1876 William Brown, a professor of agriculture and then superintendent of the experimental farm at Guelph, Ontario, was granted permission by the government of Ontario to purchase Aberdeen Angus cattle for the Ontario Agricultural College.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The herd comprised a yearling bull, Gladiolus, and a cow, Eyebright, bred by the Earl of Fife and a cow, Leochel Lass 4th, bred by R.O.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] On 12 January 1877, Eyebright gave birth to a calf, sired by Sir Wilfrid.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] It was the first to be born outside of Scotland.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The OAC went on to import additional bulls and cows, eventually began selling Aberdeen Angus cattle in 1881.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] On 17 May 1873, George Grant brought four Angus bulls, without any cows, to Victoria, Kansas.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] These were seen as unusual as the normal American cattle consisted of Shorthorns and Longhorns, and the bulls were used only in crossbreeding; however, the farmers noticed the good qualities of these bulls, and afterwards many more cattle of both sexes were imported.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] On 21 November 1883, the American Angus Association was founded in Chicago, Illinois.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The first herd book was published in March 1885.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] At this time, both red and black animals were registered without distinction. in 1917, it barred the registering of red and other coloured animals in an effort to promote a solid black breed.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The Red Angus Association of America was founded in 1954 by breeders of Red Angus cattle.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] It was formed because the breeders had had their cattle struck off the herd book for not conforming to the changed breed standard regarding colour.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] A separate breed was cross bred in Germany called the German Angus.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] It is a cross between the Angus and several different cattle such as the German Black Pied Cattle, Gelbvieh, and Fleckvieh.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The cattle are usually larger than the Angus and appear in black and red colours.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Because of their native environment, the cattle are very hardy and can survive the Scottish winters, which are often harsh, with snowfall and storms.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Cows weigh about 550 kilograms (1,210 lb) and bulls some 850 kilograms (1,870 lb).
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Bulls may be used on dairy cows to produce a beef calf.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The cattle are naturally polled and may be either black or red.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] They reach maturity earlier than some other native British breeds such as the Hereford or North Devon.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The cattle have a large muscle content and are regarded as medium-sized.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] In Japan the meat is prized for its marbling.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Among the recessive genetic defects that can affect the cattle are: arthrogryposis multiplex ("curly calf"); neuropathic hydrocephalus ("water head"); contractural arachnodactyly or "fawn calf syndrome"; dwarfism; osteoporosis; and notomelia.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The Aberdeen Angus is reared principally for beef.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Bulls are used extensively as terminal sires on cows of other breeds – particularly dairy breeds – to produce cross-bred beef calves.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] The meat can be marketed as superior due to its marbled appearance.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Bulls can also be used to transmit characteristics including the polled gene (for ease of handling) and – with the aim of lowering the incidence of dystocia – the easy calving of cows.
[src:cattle/aberdeen-angus] Many modern breeds derive from the Aberdeen Angus or from its American derivatives, the American Angus and Red Angus of the United States.
[src:cattle/abomasum] The **abomasum**, also known as the **maw**, **rennet-bag**, or **reed tripe**, is the fourth and final stomach compartment in ruminants.
[src:cattle/abomasum] It secretes rennet, which is used in cheese creation.
[src:cattle/abomasum] The word *abomasum* (*ab-* "away from" + *omasum* "intestine of an ox") is from Neo-Latin and it was first used in English in 1706.
[src:cattle/abomasum] It is possibly from the Gaulish language.
[src:cattle/abomasum] The abomasum's normal anatomical location is along the ventral midline.
[src:cattle/abomasum] It is a secretory stomach similar in anatomy and function to the monogastric stomach.
[src:cattle/abomasum] It serves primarily in the acid hydrolysis of microbial and dietary protein, preparing these protein sources for further digestion and absorption in the small intestine.
[src:cattle/abomasum] The abomasum is lined with glands to release hydrochloric acid and digestive enzymes needed to break down food.
[src:cattle/abomasum] It is very similar to the nonruminant stomach.
[src:cattle/abomasum] Dairy cattle on high production diets are susceptible to a number of pathologies, most commonly after calving.
[src:cattle/abomasum] A gas-filled abomasum can move into an abnormal location and become displaced.
[src:cattle/abomasum] If the abomasum displaces to the right, it is at risk of torsion.
[src:cattle/abomasum] A displaced abomasum will cause cows to present all or some of the following signs: loss of appetite, decrease rumen contractions, decrease cud-chewing, and drop in milk production.
[src:cattle/abomasum] While a displaced abomasum is not immediately life-threatening, veterinary care is required for surgical correction.
[src:cattle/abomasum] Milder cases can be corrected by rolling the cow over or forcing her to run up a steep hill.
[src:cattle/abomasum] Abomasitis is a relatively rare, but serious, disease of the abomasum whose causes are currently unknown.
[src:cattle/abomasum] The abomasum is used to make the *lampredotto*, a typical dish of Florence.
[src:cattle/abomasum] It is also fried and eaten with onions as part of the Korean dish *Makchang gui*.
[src:cattle/abomasum] Another dish made with the abomasum is the Persian Sirabi-Shirdan (borrowed in Turkey as *Şırdan*).
[src:cattle/abomasum] Chusta (literally abomasum) is a famous dish in Bihar, India.
[src:cattle/abomasum] In Japan, it is grilled and served as horumonyaki, this particular type of horumon is known as Akasen.
[src:cattle/acidosis] The term acidemia describes the state of low blood pH, when arterial pH falls below 7.35 (except in the fetus – see below) while *acidosis* is used to describe the processes leading to these states.
[src:cattle/acidosis] The use of acidosis for a low pH creates an ambiguity in its meaning.
[src:cattle/acidosis] The difference is important where a patient has factors causing both acidosis and alkalosis, wherein the relative severity of both determines whether the result is a high, low, or normal pH.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Arterial blood gas analysis and other tests are required to separate the main causes, which are clear in certain situations.
[src:cattle/acidosis] For instance, a diabetic with ketoacidosis is a recognizable case where the main cause of acidemia is essentially obvious.
[src:cattle/acidosis] The rate of cellular metabolic activity affects and, at the same time, is affected by the pH of the body fluids.
[src:cattle/acidosis] In mammals, the normal pH of arterial blood lies between 7.35 and 7.50 depending on the species (e.g., healthy human-arterial blood pH varies between 7.35 and 7.45).
[src:cattle/acidosis] Nervous system involvement may be seen with acidosis and occurs more often with respiratory acidosis than with metabolic acidosis.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Signs and symptoms that may be seen in acidosis include headaches, confusion, feeling tired, tremors, sleepiness, flapping tremor, and dysfunction of the cerebrum of the brain which may progress to coma if there is no intervention.
[src:cattle/acidosis] In extreme cases symptoms can be anorexia, diabetes mellitus, chronic nephritis or pneumonia.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Lactic acidosis occurs whenever the demand for oxygen by tissues exceeds the supply and the more efficient aerobic metabolism is supplemented by anaerobic metabolism that produces lactate.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Increased demand occurs, for example, with high intensity exercise such as sprinting.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Inadequate supply occurs, for example, with hypoperfusion as occurs in hemorrhagic shock.
[src:cattle/acidosis] A rise in lactate out of proportion to the level of pyruvate, e.g., in mixed venous blood, is termed "excess lactate", and is an indicator of anaerobic glycolysis occurring in muscle cells, as seen during strenuous exercise.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Once oxygenation is restored, the acidosis clears quickly.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Another example of increased production of acids occurs in starvation and diabetic ketoacidosis.
[src:cattle/acidosis] It is due to the accumulation of ketoacids (via excessive ketosis) and reflects a severe shift from glycolysis to lipolysis for energy needs.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Acid consumption from poisoning such as methanol ingestion, elevated levels of iron in the blood, and chronically decreased production of bicarbonate may also produce metabolic acidosis.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Metabolic acidosis is compensated for in the lungs, as increased exhalation of carbon dioxide promptly shifts the buffering equation to reduce metabolic acid.
[src:cattle/acidosis] This is a result of stimulation to chemoreceptors, which increases alveolar ventilation, leading to respiratory compensation, otherwise known as Kussmaul breathing (a specific type of hyperventilation).
[src:cattle/acidosis] Should this situation persist, the patient is at risk of exhaustion leading to respiratory failure.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Mutations to the V-ATPase 'a4' or 'B1' isoforms result in distal renal tubular acidosis, a condition that leads to metabolic acidosis, in some cases with sensorineural deafness.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Arterial blood gases will indicate low pH, low blood HCO3, and normal or low PaCO2.
[src:cattle/acidosis] In addition to arterial blood gas, an anion gap can also differentiate between possible causes.
[src:cattle/acidosis] The Henderson-Hasselbalch equation is useful for calculating blood pH, because blood is a buffer solution.
[src:cattle/acidosis] In the clinical setting, this equation is usually used to calculate HCO3 from measurements of pH and PaCO2 in arterial blood gases.
[src:cattle/acidosis] The amount of metabolic acid accumulating can also be quantitated by using buffer base deviation, a derivative estimate of the metabolic as opposed to the respiratory component.
[src:cattle/acidosis] In hypovolemic shock for example, approximately 50% of the metabolic acid accumulation is lactic acid, which disappears as blood flow and oxygen debt are corrected.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Treatment of uncompensated metabolic acidosis is focused upon correcting the underlying problem.
[src:cattle/acidosis] When metabolic acidosis is severe and can no longer be compensated for adequately by the lungs or kidneys, neutralizing the acidosis with infusions of bicarbonate may be required.
[src:cattle/acidosis] In the fetus, the normal range differs based on which umbilical vessel is sampled (umbilical vein pH is normally 7.25 to 7.45; umbilical artery pH is normally 7.18 to 7.38).
[src:cattle/acidosis] Fetal metabolic acidemia is defined as an umbilical vessel pH of less than 7.20 and a base excess of less than −8.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Respiratory acidosis results from a build-up of carbon dioxide in the blood (hypercapnia) due to hypoventilation.
[src:cattle/acidosis] It is most often caused by pulmonary problems, although head injuries, drugs (especially anaesthetics and sedatives), and brain tumors can cause this acidemia.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Pneumothorax, emphysema, chronic bronchitis, asthma, severe pneumonia, and aspiration are among the most frequent causes.
[src:cattle/acidosis] It can also occur as a compensatory response to chronic metabolic alkalosis.
[src:cattle/acidosis] One key to distinguish between respiratory and metabolic acidosis is that in respiratory acidosis, the CO2 is increased while the bicarbonate is either normal (uncompensated) or increased (compensated).
[src:cattle/acidosis] Compensation occurs if respiratory acidosis is present, and a chronic phase is entered with partial buffering of the acidosis through renal bicarbonate retention.
[src:cattle/acidosis] However, in cases where chronic illnesses that compromise pulmonary function persist, such as late-stage emphysema and certain types of muscular dystrophy, compensatory mechanisms will be unable to reverse this acidotic condition.
[src:cattle/acidosis] As metabolic bicarbonate production becomes exhausted, and extraneous bicarbonate infusion can no longer reverse the extreme buildup of carbon dioxide associated with uncompensated respiratory acidosis, mechanical ventilation will usually be applied.
[src:cattle/acidosis] In the fetus, the normal range differs based on which umbilical vessel is sampled (umbilical vein pH is normally 7.25 to 7.45; umbilical artery pH is normally 7.20 to 7.38).
[src:cattle/acidosis] In the fetus, the lungs are not used for ventilation.
[src:cattle/acidosis] Instead, the placenta performs ventilatory functions (gas exchange).
[src:cattle/acidosis] Fetal respiratory acidemia is defined as an umbilical vessel pH of less than 7.20 and an umbilical artery PCO2 of 66 or higher or umbilical vein PCO2 of 50 or higher.
[src:cattle/addax] The **addax** (***Addax nasomaculatus***), also known as the **white antelope** and the **screwhorn antelope**, is an antelope native to the Sahara.
[src:cattle/addax] The only member of the genus ***Addax***, it was first described scientifically by Henri de Blainville in 1816.
[src:cattle/addax] As suggested by its alternative name, the addax has spiral horns that are 55 to 80 cm (22 to 31 in) long in females and 70 to 85 cm (28 to 33 in) in males.
[src:cattle/addax] In the winter, its coat is greyish-brown with white hindquarters and legs, and long, brown hair on the head, neck, and shoulders; in the summer, the coat turns almost completely white or sandy blonde.
[src:cattle/addax] Males stand from 105 to 115 cm (41 to 45 in) at the shoulder, with females at 95 to 110 cm (37 to 43 in).
[src:cattle/addax] They are sexually dimorphic, as the females are generally smaller than the males.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax lives in arid regions, semideserts, and sandy and stony deserts in North Africa.
[src:cattle/addax] It mainly eats grasses and leaves of shrubs, leguminous herbs, and bushes.
[src:cattle/addax] It can live without water for long periods of time.
[src:cattle/addax] Addax form herds of five to 20 members, consisting of both males and females.
[src:cattle/addax] The herd is usually led by one dominant male.
[src:cattle/addax] Breeding season is at its peak during winter and early spring.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax is listed as critically endangered on the IUCN Red List.
[src:cattle/addax] It was once abundant, but is currently restricted to Chad, Mauritania, and Niger.
[src:cattle/addax] It is threatened by unregulated hunting and is locally extinct in Western Sahara, Algeria, Libya, Egypt, and Sudan.
[src:cattle/addax] The scientific name of the addax *Addax nasomaculatus* was proposed by Henri Marie Ducrotay de Blainville in 1816; he described a specimen in William Bullock's Pantherion and the Museum of the Royal College of Surgeons.
[src:cattle/addax] Its type locality is probably in the Tunisian part of the Sahara.
[src:cattle/addax] The generic name *Addax* is thought to be obtained from an Arabic word meaning a wild animal with crooked horns.
[src:cattle/addax] It is also thought to have originated from a Latin word.
[src:cattle/addax] The specific name *nasomaculatus* comes from the Latin words *nasus* (or the prefix *naso-*) meaning nose, and *maculatus* meaning spotted, referring to the spots and facial markings of the species.
[src:cattle/addax] Bedouins use another name for the addax, the Arabic *bakr* (or *bagr*) *al wahsh*, which literally means "the cow of the wild".
[src:cattle/addax] That name can be used to refer to other ungulates, as well.
[src:cattle/addax] The other common names of addax are "white antelope" and "screwhorn antelope".
[src:cattle/addax] All chromosomes are acrocentric except for the first pair of autosomes, which are submetacentric.
[src:cattle/addax] The X chromosome is the largest of the acrocentric chromosomes, and the Y chromosome is medium-sized.
[src:cattle/addax] The short and long arms of the pair of submetacentric autosomes correspond respectively to the 27th and 1st chromosomes in cattle and goats.
[src:cattle/addax] In a study, the banding patterns of chromosomes in addax were found to be similar to those in four other species of the subfamily Hippotraginae.
[src:cattle/addax] In ancient times, the addax occurred from northern Africa through Arabia and the Levant.
[src:cattle/addax] Pictures in a tomb, dating back to 2500 BCE, show at least the partial domestication of the addax by the ancient Egyptians.
[src:cattle/addax] These pictures show addax and some other antelopes tied with ropes to stakes.
[src:cattle/addax] The number of addax captured by a person were considered an indicator of his high social and economic position in the society.
[src:cattle/addax] The *pygarg* ("white-buttocked") beast mentioned in Deuteronomy 14:5 is believed by Henry Baker Tristram to have been an addax, but poaching has resulted in the extinction of this species in Egypt since the 1960s.
[src:cattle/addax] Addax fossils have been found in four sites of Egypt – a 7000 BCE fossil from the Great Sand Sea, a 5000–6000 BCE fossil from Djara, a 4000–7000 BCE fossil from Abu Ballas Stufenmland, and a 5000 BCE fossil from Gilf Kebir.
[src:cattle/addax] Apart from these, fossils have also been excavated from Mittleres Wadi Howar (6300 BCE fossil), and Pleistocene fossils from Grotte Neandertaliens, Jebel Irhoud, and Parc d'Hydra.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax is greyish-brown in winter and almost completely white or sandy blonde in summer; it has white hindquarters and legs, and long, brown hair on the head, neck, and shoulders.
[src:cattle/addax] Its head-to-body length is 120 to 130 cm (47 to 51 in), and its tail is 25 to 35 cm (9.8 to 13.8 in) long.
[src:cattle/addax] It is sexually dimorphic in size, as males stand from 105 to 115 cm (41 to 45 in) at the shoulder with a weight of 100 to 125 kg (220 to 276 lb), whereas females are 95 to 110 cm (37 to 43 in) tall with a weight of 60 to 90 kg (130 to 200 lb).
[src:cattle/addax] Their heads are marked with brown or black patches that form an X over their noses.
[src:cattle/addax] They have scraggly beards and prominent red nostrils.
[src:cattle/addax] Long, black hairs stick out between their curved and spiraling horns, ending in a short mane on the neck.
[src:cattle/addax] The horns have two to three twists and are typically 55 to 80 cm (22 to 31 in) in females and 70 to 85 cm (28 to 33 in) in males, although the maximum recorded length is 109.2 cm (43.0 in).
[src:cattle/addax] The lower and middle portions of the horns are marked with a series of 30 to 35 ring-shaped ridges.
[src:cattle/addax] The tail is short and slender, ending in a puff of black hair.
[src:cattle/addax] The hooves are broad with flat soles and strong dewclaws to help them walk on soft sand.
[src:cattle/addax] The lifespan of the addax is up to 19 years in the wild, which can be extended to 25 years in captivity.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax closely resembles the scimitar oryx, but can be distinguished by its horns and facial markings.
[src:cattle/addax] While the addax is spiral-horned, the scimitar oryx has decurved, 127 cm (50 in) long horns.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax has a brown hair tuft extending from the base of its horns to between its eyes.
[src:cattle/addax] A white patch, continuing from the brown hair, extends until the middle of the cheek.
[src:cattle/addax] The scimitar oryx, though, has a white forehead with only a notable brown marking, a brown lateral stripe across its eyes.
[src:cattle/addax] It differs from other antelopes by having large, square teeth like cattle and lacking the typical facial glands.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax inhabits arid regions, semideserts, and sandy and stony deserts.
[src:cattle/addax] It can live in extremely arid areas, with less than 100 mm (3.9 in) annual rainfall.
[src:cattle/addax] It also inhabits deserts with tussock grasses (*Stipagrostis* species) and succulent thorn scrub *Cornulaca*.
[src:cattle/addax] Formerly, the addax was widespread in the Sahelo-Saharan region of Africa, west of the Nile Valley, and all countries sharing the Sahara, but today the only known self-sustaining population is present in the Termit Massif Reserve in Niger.
[src:cattle/addax] Reports of sightings have been made from the eastern Air Mountains in Niger and Bodélé in Chad.
[src:cattle/addax] Rare nomads may be seen in northern Niger, southern Algeria, and Libya; it is rumoured to be present along the Mali/Mauritania border, though no sightings have been confirmed.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax was once abundant in North Africa, native to Chad, Mauritania, and Niger.
[src:cattle/addax] It is extinct in Algeria, Egypt, Libya, Sudan, and the Western Sahara.
[src:cattle/addax] It has been reintroduced into Morocco and Tunisia.
[src:cattle/addax] Addax herds contain both males and females, and have from five to 20 members.
[src:cattle/addax] They generally stay in one place and only wander widely in search of food.
[src:cattle/addax] The herd is usually formed around one dominant male.
[src:cattle/addax] In captivity, males show signs of territoriality and mate guarding, while captive females establish dominance hierarchies, with the oldest females holding highest rank.
[src:cattle/addax] Herds are more likely to be found along the northern edge of the tropical rain system during the summer and move north as winter falls.
[src:cattle/addax] They are able to track rainfall and head for these areas where vegetation is more plentiful.
[src:cattle/addax] Males are territorial and guard females, while the females establish their own dominance hierarchies.
[src:cattle/addax] Due to its slow movements, the addax is an easy target for predators, such as humans, lions, leopards, cheetahs, and African wild dogs.
[src:cattle/addax] Caracals, servals, and hyenas attack calves.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax is normally not aggressive, though individuals may charge if they are disturbed.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax is amply suited to live in the deep desert under extreme conditions.
[src:cattle/addax] It can survive without free water almost indefinitely, because it gets moisture from its food and dew that condenses on plants.
[src:cattle/addax] Scientists think the addax has a special lining in its stomach that stores water in pouches to use in times of dehydration.
[src:cattle/addax] It also produces highly concentrated urine to conserve water.
[src:cattle/addax] The pale colour of the coat reflects radiant heat, and the length and density of the coat helps in thermoregulation.
[src:cattle/addax] In the day, the addax huddles together in shaded areas, and on cool nights, rests in sand hollows.
[src:cattle/addax] These practices help in dissipation of body heat and saving water by cooling the body through evaporation.
[src:cattle/addax] In a study, eight addax on a diet of grass hay (*Chloris gayana*) were studied to determine the retention time of food from the digestive tract.
[src:cattle/addax] Food retention time was long, possibly as an adaptation to a diet including a high proportion of slow-fermenting grasses; the long retention time also could be interpreted to be due to water-saving mechanisms with low water turnover and a roomy rumen.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax lives in desert terrain where it eats grasses and leaves of what shrubs, leguminous herbs, and bushes are available.
[src:cattle/addax] Primarily a grazer, its staple foods include *Aristida*, *Panicum*, and *Stipagrostis*, and it only consumes browse, such as leaves of *Acacia* trees, in the absence of these grasses.
[src:cattle/addax] It also eats perennials, which turn green and sprout at the slightest bit of humidity or rain.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax eats only certain parts of the plant and tends to crop the *Aristida* grasses neatly to the same height.
[src:cattle/addax] By contrast, when feeding on *Panicum* grasses, the drier outer leaves are left alone while it eats the tender inner shoots and seeds.
[src:cattle/addax] These seeds are important part of the addax's diet, being its main source of protein.
[src:cattle/addax] Females are sexually mature at 2-3 years of age and males around 2 years.
[src:cattle/addax] Breeding occurs throughout the year, but it peaks during winter and early spring.
[src:cattle/addax] In the northern Sahara, breeding peaks at the end of winter and the beginning of spring; in the southern Sahara, breeding peaks from September to October and from January to mid-April.
[src:cattle/addax] In a study, the blood serum of female addax was analyzed through immunoassay to know about their luteal phase.
[src:cattle/addax] Estrous cycle duration was of about 33 days.
[src:cattle/addax] During pregnancy, ultrasonography showed the uterine horns as coiled.
[src:cattle/addax] The maximum diameters of the ovarian follicle and the corpus luteum were 15 mm (0.59 in) and 27 mm (1.1 in), respectively.
[src:cattle/addax] Each female underwent an anovulatory period lasting 39 to 131 days, during which no ovulation occurred.
[src:cattle/addax] Anovulation was rare in winter, which suggested the effect of seasons on the estrous cycle.
[src:cattle/addax] Gestation period lasts 257–270 days (about nine months).
[src:cattle/addax] Females may lie or stand during the delivery, during which one calf is born.
[src:cattle/addax] A postpartum estrus occurs after 2-3 days.
[src:cattle/addax] The calf weighs 5 kg (11 lb) at birth and is weaned at 23–29 weeks old.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax is most prone to parasites in moist climatic conditions.
[src:cattle/addax] Addax have always been infected with nematodes in the Trichostrongyloidea and Strongyloidea superfamilies.
[src:cattle/addax] In an exotic ranch in Texas, an addax was found host to the nematodes *Haemonchus contortus* and *Longistrongylus curvispiculum* in its abomasum, of which the former was dominant.
[src:cattle/addax] Declines in the population of the addax have been ongoing since the mid-1800s.
[src:cattle/addax] More recently, addax were found from Algeria to Sudan, but due mainly to overhunting, they have become much more restricted and rare.
[src:cattle/addax] Addax are easy to hunt due to their slow movements.
[src:cattle/addax] Roadkill, firearms for easy hunting, and nomadic settlements near waterholes (their dry-season feeding places) have also decreased their numbers.
[src:cattle/addax] Moreover, their meat and leather are highly prized.
[src:cattle/addax] Other threats include chronic droughts in the deserts, habitat destruction due to more human settlements, and agriculture.
[src:cattle/addax] Fewer than 500 individuals are thought to exist in the wild today, most of the animals being found between the Termit area of Niger, the Bodélé region of western Chad, and the Aoukar in Mauritania.
[src:cattle/addax] Today, over 600 addax are in Europe, Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve, Sabratha, Giza Zoo, North America, Japan, and Australia under captive-breeding programmes.
[src:cattle/addax] Thousands more are in private collections and ranches in the United States and the Middle East.
[src:cattle/addax] Addax are legally protected in Morocco, Tunisia, and Algeria; hunting of all gazelles is forbidden in Libya and Egypt.
[src:cattle/addax] The addax has been reintroduced into Bou-Hedma National Park (Tunisia) and Souss-Massa National Park (Morocco).
[src:cattle/addax] Reintroductions in the wild are ongoing in Jebil National Park (Tunisia) and Grand Erg Oriental (the Sahara), and another is planned for Morocco.
[src:cattle/addax] Whether any of the last remaining wild addax in western Chad near the Niger border still survive is uncertain.
[src:cattle/addax] In 2019, Sahara Conservation Fund in partnership with the Environment Agency Abu Dhabi began a project to reintroduce addax to the Ouadi Rimé-Ouadi Achim Faunal Reserve, and a small population now exists there.
[src:cattle/addax] In 2023, 10 addax were moved to Ennedi Natural and Cultural Reserve.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] The Aders's duiker stands at around 30 cm (12 in) tall at the shoulder.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] Its weight varies greatly depending on geographical location; those in eastern Zanzibar weigh 12 kg (26 lb), while those in the south weigh only 7.5 kg (17 lb).
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] Its coat is reddish-brown, grayer on the neck, and lighter down the backside and underneath.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] It also has small, simple horns of 3 to 6 cm (1.2 to 2.4 in).
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] The muzzle is pointed, and the nose has a flat front.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] The ears measure 7.0–8.3 cm (2.8–3.3 in) long, with a marked cowlick or whorl of hair on the nape of the neck.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] Aders's duikers live primarily in coastal forests and woodlands in Africa.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] The species can live in quite dry scrub near the sea or among coral outcrops; in Zanzibar, they are restricted to tall thicket forest growing on waterless coral rag.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] In Arabuko Sokoke (Kenya), they are most often trapped within *Cynometra* vegetation, especially on "red soil".
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] *C. adersi* is sympatric with *C. harveyi* on the mainland and with *C. monticola sundevalli* on Zanzibar, although nothing is known regarding their ecological separation.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] The species is very shy, alert, and sensitive to sound.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] As a result, common methods of hunting include the brute-force method of driving the duikers into nets with dogs, or silent ambush at feeding sites.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] Aders's duikers live in coastal forests, thickets and woodlands, where they eat flowers, leaves, and fruit which has fallen from the forest canopy.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] The species appears to be diurnal, as it is rarely seen active at night.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] Typical feeding patterns are from dawn to late morning, which is followed by a period of rest and rumination.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] At midafternoon, Aders's duikers generally become active, and will continue foraging until nightfall.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] They are generally solitary or found in small groups of two or three.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] They often pick up scraps dropped by monkeys and birds foraging in the trees.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] In addition to these, they will eat sprouts, buds, and other fresh growth found at ground level.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] This duiker species can apparently manage without drinking, getting most of the hydration they need from their diets.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] These duikers have extremely specific habitat requirements, being found only in areas of old-growth thicket, with the highest population densities (11.4±5.18 per km2) recorded in relatively undisturbed high thicket.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] However, Kanga (1999) did report some Aders's duikers in secondary thicket.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] In the Arabuko-Sokoke Forest in Kenya, Aders's duikers inhabit regions of *Cyanometra* forest.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] Not much is known of its reproductive habits, although they may breed all year long.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] They are threatened by habitat destruction, feral dogs, and overhunting.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] They are particularly sought by humans due to their soft skin and meat.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] The population in Zanzibar had declined from 5000 in 1983 to 640 in 1999, and it will probably continue to decrease rapidly.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] In Kenya, the duiker is present at very low densities, though the decline is probably not as severe as the other population.
[src:cattle/aders-s-duiker] Several conservation plans have been made, and a captive-breeding program has been proposed.
[src:cattle/cattle] Taurine cattle are widely distributed across Europe and temperate areas of Asia, the Americas, and Australia.
[src:cattle/cattle] Zebus are found mainly in India and tropical areas of Asia, America, and Australia.
[src:cattle/cattle] Sanga cattle are found primarily in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:cattle/cattle] These types, sometimes classified as separate species or subspecies, are further divided into over 1,000 recognized breeds.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle are commonly raised for meat, for dairy products, and for leather.
[src:cattle/cattle] As draft animals, they pull carts and farm implements.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle are considered sacred animals within Hinduism, and it is illegal to kill them in some parts of the Indian subcontinent.
[src:cattle/cattle] Small breeds such as the miniature Zebu are kept as pets.
[src:cattle/cattle] About 10,500 years ago, taurine cattle were domesticated from wild aurochs progenitors in central Anatolia, the Levant and Western Iran.
[src:cattle/cattle] A separate domestication event occurred in the Indian subcontinent, which gave rise to zebu.
[src:cattle/cattle] There were over 940 million cattle in the world by 2022.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle farming is responsible for about 7% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:cattle/cattle] They were one of the first domesticated animals to have a fully-mapped genome.
[src:cattle/cattle] The term *cattle* was borrowed from Anglo-Norman *catel* (replacing native Old English terms like *kine*, now considered archaic, poetic, or dialectal), itself from Medieval Latin *capitāle* 'principal sum of money, capital', itself derived in turn from Latin *caput* 'head'.
[src:cattle/cattle] *Cattle* originally meant movable personal property, especially livestock of any kind, as opposed to real property (the land, which also included wild or small free-roaming animals such as chickens—they were sold as part of the land).
[src:cattle/cattle] The word is a variant of *chattel* (a unit of personal property) and closely related to *capital* in the economic sense.
[src:cattle/cattle] The word *cow* came via Old English *cū* (plural *cȳ*), from Proto-Indo-European **gʷṓws* (genitive **gʷéws*) 'a bovine animal', cf.
[src:cattle/cattle] In older English sources such as the King James Version of the Bible, *cattle* often means livestock, as opposed to *deer*, which are wild.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle are large artiodactyls, mammals with cloven hooves, meaning that they walk on two toes, the third and fourth digits.
[src:cattle/cattle] Like all bovid species, they can have horns, which are unbranched and are not shed annually.
[src:cattle/cattle] Coloration varies with breed; common colors are black, white, and red/brown, and some breeds are spotted or have mixed colors.
[src:cattle/cattle] Bulls are larger than cows of the same breed by up to a few hundred kilograms.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle breeds vary widely in size; the tallest and heaviest is the Chianina, where a mature bull may be up to 1.8 m (5 ft 11 in) at the shoulder, and may reach 1,280 kg (2,820 lb) in weight.
[src:cattle/cattle] The natural life of domestic cattle is some 25–30 years.
[src:cattle/cattle] Beef cattle go to slaughter at about 18 months, and dairy cows at about five years.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle are ruminants, meaning their digestive system is highly specialized for processing plant material such as grass rich in cellulose, a tough carbohydrate polymer which many animals cannot digest.
[src:cattle/cattle] They do this in symbiosis with micro-organisms – bacteria, fungi, and protozoa – that possess cellulases, enzymes that split cellulose into its constituent sugars.
[src:cattle/cattle] Among the many bacteria that contribute are *Fibrobacter succinogenes*, *Ruminococcus flavefaciens*, and *Ruminococcus albus*.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cellulolytic fungi include several species of *Neocallimastix*, while the protozoa include the ciliates *Eudiplodinium maggie* and *Ostracodinium album*.
[src:cattle/cattle] If the animal's feed changes over time, the composition of this microbiome changes in response.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle have one large stomach with four compartments; the rumen, reticulum, omasum, and abomasum.
[src:cattle/cattle] The rumen is the largest compartment and it harbours the most important parts of the microbiome.
[src:cattle/cattle] The reticulum, the smallest compartment, is known as the "honeycomb".
[src:cattle/cattle] The omasum's main function is to absorb water and nutrients from the digestible feed.
[src:cattle/cattle] The abomasum has a similar function to the human stomach.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle regurgitate and re-chew their food in the process of chewing the cud, like most ruminants.
[src:cattle/cattle] While feeding, cows swallow their food without chewing; it goes into the rumen for storage.
[src:cattle/cattle] Later, the food is regurgitated to the mouth, a mouthful at a time, where the cud is chewed by the molars, grinding down the coarse vegetation to small particles.
[src:cattle/cattle] The cud is then swallowed again and further digested by the micro-organisms in the cow's stomach.
[src:cattle/cattle] The gestation period for a cow is about nine months long.
[src:cattle/cattle] The ratio of male to female offspring at birth is approximately 52:48.
[src:cattle/cattle] A cow's udder has two pairs of mammary glands or teats.
[src:cattle/cattle] Farms often use artificial insemination, the artificial deposition of semen in the female's genital tract; this allows farmers to choose from a wide range of bulls to breed their cattle.
[src:cattle/cattle] Estrus too may be artificially induced to facilitate the process.
[src:cattle/cattle] Copulation lasts several seconds and consists of a single pelvic thrust.
[src:cattle/cattle] After their first mating, semi-wild Highland cattle heiffers first give birth at 2 or 3 years of age, and the timing of birth is synchronized with increases in natural food quality.
[src:cattle/cattle] Average calving interval is 391 days, and calving mortality within the first year of life is 5%.
[src:cattle/cattle] Beef calves suckle an average of 5 times per day, spending some 46 minutes suckling.
[src:cattle/cattle] There is a diurnal rhythm in suckling, peaking at roughly 6am, 11:30am, and 7pm.
[src:cattle/cattle] Under natural conditions, calves stay with their mother until weaning at 8 to 11 months.
[src:cattle/cattle] Heiffer and bull calves are equally attached to their mothers in the first few months of life.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle have a variety of cognitive abilities.
[src:cattle/cattle] They can memorize the locations of multiple food sources, and can retain memories for at least 48 days.
[src:cattle/cattle] Young cattle learn more quickly than adults.
[src:cattle/cattle] Calves are capable of discrimination learning, distinguishing familiar and unfamiliar animals, and between humans, using faces and other cues.
[src:cattle/cattle] Calves prefer their own mother's vocalizations to those of an unfamiliar cow.
[src:cattle/cattle] Vocalizations provide information on the age, sex, dominance status and reproductive status of the caller, and may indicate estrus in cows and competitive display in bulls.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cows can categorize images as familiar and unfamiliar individuals.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cloned calves from the same donor form subgroups, suggesting that kin discrimination may be a basis of grouping behaviour.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle use visual/brain lateralisation when scanning novel and familiar stimuli.
[src:cattle/cattle] They prefer to view novel stimuli with the left eye (using the right brain hemisphere), but the right eye for familiar stimuli.
[src:cattle/cattle] Individual cattle have also been observed to display different personality traits, such as fearfulness and sociability.
[src:cattle/cattle] A case of multi-purpose tool use has been documented, where a cow named Veronika uses different ends of a deck brush to scratch different parts of her body.
[src:cattle/cattle] Vision is the dominant sense; cattle obtain almost half of their information visually.
[src:cattle/cattle] Being prey animals, cattle evolved to look out for predators almost all around, with eyes that are on the sides of their head rather than the front.
[src:cattle/cattle] This gives them a field of view of 330°, but limits binocular vision (and therefore stereopsis) to some 30° to 50°, compared to 140° in humans.
[src:cattle/cattle] They are dichromatic, like most mammals.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle avoid bitter-tasting foods, selecting sweet foods for energy.
[src:cattle/cattle] Their sensitivity to sour-tasting foods helps them to maintain optimal ruminal pH.
[src:cattle/cattle] They seek out salty foods by taste and smell to maintain their electrolyte balance.
[src:cattle/cattle] Their hearing is better than that of horses, but worse at localising sounds than goats, and much worse than dogs or humans.
[src:cattle/cattle] They can distinguish between live and recorded human speech.
[src:cattle/cattle] Olfaction probably plays a large role in their social life, indicating social and reproductive status.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle can tell when other animals are stressed by smelling the alarm chemicals in their urine.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle can be trained to recognise conspecific individuals using olfaction only.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle often engage in mock fights where they test each other's strength in a non-aggressive way.
[src:cattle/cattle] Licking is primarily performed by subordinates and received by dominant animals.
[src:cattle/cattle] Mounting is a playful behavior shown by calves of both sexes and by bulls and sometimes by cows in estrus, however, this is not a dominance related behavior as has been found in other species.
[src:cattle/cattle] Dominance-associated aggressiveness does not correlate with rank position, but is closely related to rank distance between individuals.
[src:cattle/cattle] The horns of cattle are used in mate selection.
[src:cattle/cattle] Horned cattle attempt to keep greater distances between themselves and have fewer physical interactions than hornless cattle, resulting in more stable social relationships.
[src:cattle/cattle] In calves, agonistic behavior becomes less frequent as space allowance increases, but not as group size changes, whereas in adults, the number of agonistic encounters increases with group size.
[src:cattle/cattle] Dominance relationships in semi-wild highland cattle are very firm, with few overt aggressive conflicts: most disputes are settled by agonistic (non-aggressive, competitive) behaviors with no physical contact between opponents, reducing the risk of injury.
[src:cattle/cattle] Dominance status depends on age and sex, with older animals usually dominant to young ones and males dominant to females.
[src:cattle/cattle] Young bulls gain superior dominance status over adult cows when they reach about 2 years of age.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle eat mixed diets, but prefer to eat approximately 70% clover and 30% grass.
[src:cattle/cattle] This preference has a diurnal pattern, with a stronger preference for clover in the morning, and the proportion of grass increasing towards the evening.
[src:cattle/cattle] When grazing, cattle vary several aspects of their bite, i.e. tongue and jaw movements, depending on characteristics of the plant they are eating.
[src:cattle/cattle] Bite area decreases with the density of the plants but increases with their height.
[src:cattle/cattle] Bite area is determined by the sweep of the tongue; in one study observing 750-kilogram (1,650 lb) steers, bite area reached a maximum of approximately 170 cm2 (30 sq in).
[src:cattle/cattle] Bite depth increases with the height of the plants.
[src:cattle/cattle] By adjusting their behavior, cattle obtain heavier bites in swards that are tall and sparse compared with short, dense swards of equal mass/area.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle adjust other aspects of their grazing behavior in relation to the available food; foraging velocity decreases and intake rate increases in areas of abundant palatable forage.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle avoid grazing areas contaminated by the faeces of other cattle more strongly than they avoid areas contaminated by sheep, but they do not avoid pasture contaminated by rabbits.
[src:cattle/cattle] In cattle, temperament or behavioral disposition can affect productivity, overall health, and reproduction.
[src:cattle/cattle] Five underlying categories of temperament traits have been proposed: shyness–boldness, exploration–avoidance, activity, aggressiveness, and sociability.
[src:cattle/cattle] There are many indicators of emotion in cattle.
[src:cattle/cattle] Holstein–Friesian heifers that had made clear improvements in a learning experiment had higher heart rates, indicating an emotional reaction to their own learning.
[src:cattle/cattle] After separation from their mothers, Holstein calves react, indicating low mood.
[src:cattle/cattle] Similarly, after hot-iron dehorning, calves react to the post-operative pain.
[src:cattle/cattle] The position of the ears has been used as an indicator of emotional state.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle can tell when other cattle are stressed by the chemicals in their urine.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle are gregarious, and even short-term isolation causes psychological stress.
[src:cattle/cattle] When heifers are isolated, vocalizations, heart rate and plasma cortisol all increase.
[src:cattle/cattle] When visual contact is re-instated, vocalizations rapidly decline; heart rate decreases more rapidly if the returning cattle are familiar to the previously isolated individual.
[src:cattle/cattle] Mirrors have been used to reduce stress in isolated cattle.
[src:cattle/cattle] The average sleep time of a domestic cow is about 4 hours a day.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle do have a stay apparatus, but do not sleep standing up; they lie down to sleep deeply.
[src:cattle/cattle] In 2009, the National Institutes of Health and the US Department of Agriculture reported having mapped the bovine genome.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle have some 22,000 genes, of which 80% are shared with humans; they have about 1000 genes that they share with dogs and rodents, but not with humans.
[src:cattle/cattle] Using this bovine "HapMap", researchers can track the differences between breeds that affect meat and milk yields.
[src:cattle/cattle] Early research focused on Hereford genetic sequences; a wider study mapped a further 4.2% of the cattle genome.
[src:cattle/cattle] Behavioral traits of cattle can be as heritable as some production traits, and often, the two can be related.
[src:cattle/cattle] The heritability of temperament (response to isolation during handling) has been calculated as 0.36 and 0.46 for habituation to handling.
[src:cattle/cattle] Rangeland assessments show that the heritability of aggressiveness in cattle is about 0.36.
[src:cattle/cattle] Quantitative trait loci have been found for a range of production and behavioral characteristics for both dairy and beef cattle.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle have played a key role in human history, having been domesticated since at least the early Neolithic age.
[src:cattle/cattle] Archaeozoological and genetic data indicate that cattle were first domesticated from wild aurochs (*Bos primigenius*) approximately 10,500 years ago.
[src:cattle/cattle] There were two major areas of domestication: one in central Anatolia, the Levant, and Western Iran, which gave rise to the taurine line, and a second in the area that is now Pakistan, which produced the indicine line.
[src:cattle/cattle] Modern mitochondrial DNA variation indicates the taurine line may have arisen from as few as 80 aurochs tamed in the upper reaches of Mesopotamia near the villages of Çayönü Tepesi, in what is now southeastern Turkey, and Dja'de el-Mughara, in what is now northern Syria.
[src:cattle/cattle] Although European cattle are largely descended from the taurine lineage, gene flow from African cattle (partially of indicine origin) contributed substantial genomic components to both southern European cattle breeds and their New World descendants.
[src:cattle/cattle] A study on 134 breeds showed that modern taurine cattle originated from Africa, Asia, North and South America, Australia, and Europe.
[src:cattle/cattle] Some researchers have suggested that African taurine cattle are derived from a third independent domestication from the North African aurochs.
[src:cattle/cattle] Whether there have been two or three domestications, European, African, and Asian cattle share much of their genomes, both through their species ancestry and through repeated migrations of livestock and genetic material between species, as shown in the diagram.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle were originally identified as three separate species: *Bos taurus*, the European or "taurine" cattle (including similar types from Africa and Asia); *Bos indicus*, the Indicine or "zebu"; and the extinct *Bos primigenius*, the aurochs.
[src:cattle/cattle] The aurochs is ancestral to both zebu and taurine cattle.
[src:cattle/cattle] They were later reclassified as one species, *Bos taurus*, with the aurochs (*B. t. primigenius*), zebu (*B. t. indicus*), and taurine (*B. t. taurus*) cattle as subspecies.
[src:cattle/cattle] However, this taxonomy is contentious, and authorities such as the American Society of Mammalogists treat these taxa as separate species.
[src:cattle/cattle] Complicating the matter is the ability of cattle to interbreed with other closely related species.
[src:cattle/cattle] Hybrid individuals and even breeds exist, not only between taurine cattle and zebu (such as the sanga cattle (*Bos taurus africanus* x *Bos indicus*), but also between one or both of these and some other members of the genus *Bos* – yaks (the dzo or yattle), banteng, and gaur.
[src:cattle/cattle] Hybrids such as the beefalo breed can even occur between taurine cattle and either species of bison, leading some authors to consider the latter part of the genus *Bos*, as well.
[src:cattle/cattle] The hybrid origin of some types may not be obvious – for example, genetic testing of the Dwarf Lulu breed, the only taurine-type cattle in Nepal, found them to be a mix of taurine cattle, zebu, and yak.
[src:cattle/cattle] The aurochs originally ranged throughout Europe, North Africa, and much of Asia.
[src:cattle/cattle] In historical times, its range became restricted to Europe, and the last known individual died in Mazovia, Poland, around 1627.
[src:cattle/cattle] Breeders have attempted to recreate a similar appearance to that of the aurochs by crossing traditional types of domesticated cattle, producing the Heck breed.
[src:cattle/cattle] A group of taurine-type cattle exist in Africa; these represent either an independent domestication event or the result of crossing taurines domesticated elsewhere with local aurochs, but they are genetically distinct; some authors name them as a separate subspecies, *Bos taurus africanus*.
[src:cattle/cattle] The only pure African taurine breeds remaining are the N'Dama, Kuri and some varieties of the West African Shorthorn.
[src:cattle/cattle] Feral cattle are those that have been allowed to go wild.
[src:cattle/cattle] Feral populations exist in many parts of the world, sometimes on small islands.
[src:cattle/cattle] Some, such as Amsterdam Island cattle, Chillingham cattle, and Aleutian wild cattle, have become sufficiently distinct to be described as breeds.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle are often raised by allowing herds to graze on the grasses of large tracts of rangeland.
[src:cattle/cattle] Raising cattle extensively in this manner allows the use of land that might be unsuitable for growing crops.
[src:cattle/cattle] The most common interactions with cattle involve daily feeding, cleaning and milking.
[src:cattle/cattle] Many routine husbandry practices involve ear tagging, dehorning, loading, medical operations, artificial insemination, vaccinations and hoof care, as well as training for agricultural shows and preparations.
[src:cattle/cattle] Around the world, Fulani husbandry rests on behavioural techniques, whereas in Europe, cattle are controlled primarily by physical means, such as fences.
[src:cattle/cattle] Breeders use cattle husbandry to reduce tuberculosis susceptibility by selective breeding and maintaining herd health to avoid concurrent disease.
[src:cattle/cattle] In the United States, many cattle are raised intensively, kept in concentrated animal feeding operations, meaning there are at least 700 mature dairy cows or at least 1000 other cattle stabled or confined in a feedlot for "45 days or more in a 12-month period".
[src:cattle/cattle] Historically, the cattle population of Britain rose from 9.8 million in 1878 to 11.7 million in 1908, but beef consumption rose much faster.
[src:cattle/cattle] Britain became the "stud farm of the world" exporting livestock to countries where there were no indigenous cattle.
[src:cattle/cattle] In 1929 80% of the meat trade of the world was products of what were originally English breeds.
[src:cattle/cattle] There were nearly 70 million cattle in the US by the early 1930s.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle have the largest biomass of any animal species on Earth, at roughly 400 million tonnes, followed closely by Antarctic krill at 379 million tonnes and humans at 373 million tonnes.
[src:cattle/cattle] In 2023, the countries with the most cattle were India with 307.5 million (32.6% of the total), Brazil with 194.4 million, and China with 101.5 million, out of a total of 942.6 million in the world.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle are kept on farms to produce meat, milk, and leather, and sometimes to pull carts or farm implements.
[src:cattle/cattle] The meat of adult cattle is known as beef, and that of calves as veal.
[src:cattle/cattle] Other body parts are used as food products, including blood, liver, kidney, heart and oxtail.
[src:cattle/cattle] Approximately 300 million cattle, including dairy animals, are slaughtered each year for food.
[src:cattle/cattle] About a quarter of the world's meat comes from cattle.
[src:cattle/cattle] World cattle meat production in 2021 was 72.3 million tons.
[src:cattle/cattle] Certain breeds of cattle, such as the Holstein-Friesian, are used to produce milk, much of which is processed into dairy products such as butter, cheese, and yogurt.
[src:cattle/cattle] Dairy cattle are usually kept on specialized dairy farms designed for milk production.
[src:cattle/cattle] Most cows are milked twice per day, with milk processed at a dairy, which may be onsite at the farm or the milk may be shipped to a dairy plant for eventual sale of a dairy product.
[src:cattle/cattle] Lactation is induced in heifers and spayed cows by a combination of physical and psychological stimulation, by drugs, or by a combination of those methods.
[src:cattle/cattle] For mother cows to continue producing milk, they give birth to one calf per year.
[src:cattle/cattle] If the calf is male, it is generally slaughtered at a young age to produce veal.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cows produce milk until three weeks before birth.
[src:cattle/cattle] Over the last fifty years, dairy farming has become more intensive to increase the yield of milk produced by each cow.
[src:cattle/cattle] The Holstein-Friesian is the breed of dairy cow most common in the UK, Europe and the United States.
[src:cattle/cattle] It has been bred selectively to produce the highest yields of milk of any cow.
[src:cattle/cattle] The average in the UK is about 22 litres per day.
[src:cattle/cattle] In 2023, the 27 European Union countries produced 143 million tons of cow's milk; the United States 104.1 million tons; and India 99.5 million tons.
[src:cattle/cattle] India further produces 94.4 million tons of buffalo milk, making it (in 2023) the world's largest milk producer; its dairy industry employs some 80 million people.
[src:cattle/cattle] Oxen are cattle trained as draft animals.
[src:cattle/cattle] Oxen can pull heavier loads and for a longer period of time than horses.
[src:cattle/cattle] Oxen are used worldwide, especially in developing countries.
[src:cattle/cattle] There are some 11 million draft oxen in sub-Saharan Africa, while in 1998 India had over 65 million oxen.
[src:cattle/cattle] At the start of the 21st century, about half the world's crop production depended on land preparation by draft animals.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle are not often kept solely for hides, and they are usually a by-product of beef production.
[src:cattle/cattle] Hides are used mainly for leather products such as shoes.
[src:cattle/cattle] In 2012, India was the world's largest producer of cattle hides.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle hides account for about 65% of the world's leather production.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle are subject to pests including arthropod parasites such as ticks (which can in turn transmit diseases caused by bacteria and protozoa), and diseases caused by pathogens including bacteria and viruses.
[src:cattle/cattle] Some viral diseases are spread by insects—i.e. bluetongue disease is spread by midges.
[src:cattle/cattle] Psoroptic mange is a disabling skin condition caused by mites.
[src:cattle/cattle] Bovine tuberculosis is caused by a bacterium; it causes disease in humans and in wild animals such as deer and badgers.
[src:cattle/cattle] Foot-and-mouth disease is caused by a virus, affects a range of hoofed livestock and is highly contagious.
[src:cattle/cattle] Bovine spongiform encephalopathy is a neurodegenerative disease spread by a prion, a misfolded brain protein, in contaminated meat.
[src:cattle/cattle] Among the intestinal parasites of cattle are *Paramphistomum* flukes, affecting the rumen, and hookworms in the small intestine.
[src:cattle/cattle] Climate change is expected to exacerbate heat stress in cattle, and for longer periods.
[src:cattle/cattle] Heat-stressed cattle may experience accelerated breakdown of adipose tissue by the liver, causing lipidosis.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle eat less when heat stressed, resulting in ruminal acidosis, which can lead to laminitis.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle can attempt to deal with higher temperatures by panting more often; this rapidly decreases carbon dioxide concentrations at the price of increasing pH, respiratory alkalosis.
[src:cattle/cattle] To deal with this, cattle are forced to shed bicarbonate through urination, at the expense of rumen buffering.
[src:cattle/cattle] These two pathologies can both cause lameness.
[src:cattle/cattle] This worsens as *Calliphora* blowflies increase in number with continued warming, spreading mastitis-causing bacteria.
[src:cattle/cattle] Ticks too are likely to increase in temperate zones as the climate warms, increasing the risk of tick-borne diseases.
[src:cattle/cattle] Both beef and milk production are likely to experience declines due to climate change.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle health is at once a veterinary issue (for animal welfare and productivity), a public health issue (to limit the spread of disease), and a food safety issue (to ensure meat and dairy products are safe to eat).
[src:cattle/cattle] These concerns are reflected in farming regulations.
[src:cattle/cattle] These rules can become political matters, as when it was proposed in the UK in 2011 that milk from tuberculosis-infected cattle should be allowed to enter the food chain.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle disease attracted attention in the 1980s and 1990s when bovine spongiform encephalopathy (mad cow disease) broke out in the United Kingdom.
[src:cattle/cattle] BSE can cross into humans as the deadly variant Creutzfeldt–Jakob disease; 178 people in the UK had died from it by 2010.
[src:cattle/cattle] The gut flora of cattle produce methane, a powerful greenhouse gas, as a byproduct of enteric fermentation, with each cow belching out 100kg a year.
[src:cattle/cattle] Additional methane is produced by anaerobic fermentation of stored manure.
[src:cattle/cattle] The FAO estimates that in 2015, about 7% of global greenhouse gas emissions were due to cattle farming.
[src:cattle/cattle] Reducing methane emissions quickly helps limit climate change.
[src:cattle/cattle] Concentrated animal feeding operations in particular produce substantial amounts of wastewater and manure, which can cause environmental harms such as soil erosion, human and animal exposure to toxic chemicals, development of antibiotic resistant bacteria and an increase in *E. coli* contamination.
[src:cattle/cattle] In many world regions, overgrazing by cattle has reduced biodiversity of the grazed plants and of animals at different trophic levels in the ecosystem.
[src:cattle/cattle] A well documented consequence of overgrazing is woody plant encroachment in rangelands, which significantly reduces the carrying capacity of the land over time.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle husbandry practices including branding, castration, dehorning, ear tagging, nose ringing, restraint, tail docking, the use of veal crates, and cattle prods have raised welfare concerns.
[src:cattle/cattle] Stocking density is the number of animals within a specified area.
[src:cattle/cattle] High stocking density can affect cattle health, welfare, productivity, and feeding behaviour.
[src:cattle/cattle] Densely-stocked cattle feed more rapidly and lie down sooner, increasing the risk of teat infection, mastitis, and embryo loss.
[src:cattle/cattle] The stress and negative health impacts induced by high stocking density such as in concentrated animal feeding operations or feedlots, auctions, and transport may be detrimental to cattle welfare.
[src:cattle/cattle] To produce milk, most calves are separated from their mothers soon after birth and fed milk replacement to retain the cows' milk for human consumption.
[src:cattle/cattle] Dairy cattle are frequently artificially inseminated.
[src:cattle/cattle] Animal welfare advocates are critical of this practice, stating that this breaks the natural bond between the mother and her calf.
[src:cattle/cattle] The welfare of veal calves is also a concern.
[src:cattle/cattle] Two sports involving cattle are thought to be cruel by animal welfare groups: rodeos and bullfighting.
[src:cattle/cattle] Such groups oppose rodeo activities including bull riding, calf roping and steer roping, stating that rodeos are unnecessary and cause stress, injury, and death to the animals.
[src:cattle/cattle] In Spain, the Running of the bulls faces opposition due to the stress and injuries incurred by the bulls during the event.
[src:cattle/cattle] From early in civilisation, cattle have been used in barter.
[src:cattle/cattle] Cattle play a part in several religions.
[src:cattle/cattle] Veneration of the cow is a symbol of Hindu community identity.
[src:cattle/cattle] Slaughter of cows is forbidden by law in several states of the Indian Union, and in Nepal.
[src:cattle/cattle] The ox is one of the 12-year cycle of animals which appear in the Chinese zodiac.
[src:cattle/cattle] The astrological sign Taurus is represented as a bull in the Western zodiac.
